{
  "id": "ser-vs-estar",
  "title": "Ser vs Estar",
  "order": 3,
  "summary": "Catalan has two verbs meaning 'to be'. Which you use depends on what you're describing.",
  "sections": [
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": "One of the trickiest things for English speakers learning Catalan (and Spanish) is that there are two separate verbs that both translate as 'to be': 'ser' and 'estar'. The choice between them is not random — it follows clear rules."
    },
    {
      "type": "rule",
      "content": "Use SER for permanent or defining characteristics: identity, origin, material, time, and inherent qualities."
    },
    {
      "type": "examples",
      "items": [
        {
          "catalan": "Soc anglès",
          "english": "I am English",
          "note": "origin/identity — ser"
        },
        {
          "catalan": "És metge",
          "english": "He/she is a doctor",
          "note": "profession — ser"
        },
        {
          "catalan": "Avui és dilluns",
          "english": "Today is Monday",
          "note": "time — ser"
        },
        {
          "catalan": "La taula és de fusta",
          "english": "The table is made of wood",
          "note": "material — ser"
        },
        {
          "catalan": "Ets molt alt",
          "english": "You are very tall",
          "note": "inherent physical quality — ser"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "rule",
      "content": "Use ESTAR for temporary states, location, and conditions that can change: how someone feels, where something is, ongoing actions."
    },
    {
      "type": "examples",
      "items": [
        {
          "catalan": "Estic cansat",
          "english": "I am tired",
          "note": "temporary state — estar"
        },
        {
          "catalan": "On ets?",
          "english": "Where are you?",
          "note": "location — estar"
        },
        {
          "catalan": "El restaurant està tancat",
          "english": "The restaurant is closed",
          "note": "temporary state — estar"
        },
        {
          "catalan": "Estem a Barcelona",
          "english": "We are in Barcelona",
          "note": "location — estar"
        },
        {
          "catalan": "Com estàs?",
          "english": "How are you?",
          "note": "current state — estar (you know this from the starter deck!)"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": "Here are the present tense conjugations of both verbs — you'll need them constantly."
    },
    {
      "type": "examples",
      "items": [
        {
          "catalan": "jo soc / jo estic",
          "english": "I am",
          "note": "ser / estar"
        },
        {
          "catalan": "tu ets / tu estàs",
          "english": "you are (informal)",
          "note": "ser / estar"
        },
        {
          "catalan": "ell és / ell està",
          "english": "he/she is",
          "note": "ser / estar"
        },
        {
          "catalan": "nosaltres som / nosaltres estem",
          "english": "we are",
          "note": "ser / estar"
        },
        {
          "catalan": "vosaltres sou / vosaltres esteu",
          "english": "you are (plural)",
          "note": "ser / estar"
        },
        {
          "catalan": "ells són / ells estan",
          "english": "they are",
          "note": "ser / estar"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "practice": [
    {
